{{Infobox baseball biography |name=Andy Allison |image= |position=[[First baseman]] |bats=Unknown |throws=Unknown |birth_date=1848 |birth_place=New York City |death_date={{death date and age|1897|3|21|1848||}} |death_place=[[Brooklyn, New York]] |debutleague = MLB |debutdate=May 7 |debutyear=1872 |debutteam=[[Brooklyn Eckfords]] |finalleague = MLB |finaldate=October 21 |finalyear=1872 |finalteam=[[Brooklyn Eckfords]] |statleague = MLB |stat1label=[[Games played]] |stat1value=24 |stat2label=[[Run (baseball)|Runs scored]] |stat2value=11 |stat3label=[[Hit (baseball)|Hits]] |stat3value=15 |stat4label=[[Batting average]] |stat4value=.161 |teams= ;&nbsp; National Association of Base Ball Players : [[Brooklyn Eckfords]] (1867&ndash;1870) ;&nbsp; National Association of Professional BBP : [[Brooklyn Eckfords]] ({{baseball year|1872}}) }}
'''Andrew Kent Allison''' (1848 – March 21, 1897) was a professional baseball player who played [[first base]] in [[Major League Baseball]] for the 1872 [[Brooklyn Eckfords]]. He was the older brother of Eckfords teammate [[Bill Allison (baseball)|Bill Allison]].<ref name="founders">{{cite book|last1=Morris|first1=Peter|last2=Ryczek|first2=William J.|last3=Finkel|first3=Jan|last4=Levin|first4=Leonard|title=Base Ball Founders: The Clubs, Players and Cities of the Northeast That Established the Game|date=2013|publisher=McFarland|isbn=9780786474301|page=175|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6b6G765CzTsC&pg=PA175|accessdate=August 8, 2017|language=en}}</ref>
Allison was born in New York City, the son of Scottish immigrants James and Jane Allison.<ref name="founders"/><ref>1860 United States Federal Census</ref> In 1871, he married Elizabeth Holzberger at Ainslie St Presbyterian Church in Brooklyn.<ref>''U.S., Presbyterian Church Records, 1701-1970''</ref>
