'''Elizabeth de Mowbray, Duchess of Norfolk''' (''née'' '''Talbot'''; {{circa}} December 1442/January 1443 – 6 November 1506/10 May 1507) was a daughter of [[John Talbot, 1st Earl of Shrewsbury]] and his wife [[Margaret Talbot, Countess of Shrewsbury|Lady Margaret Beauchamp]].

==Family==
Lady Elizabeth Talbot was a daughter of [[John Talbot, 1st Earl of Shrewsbury]] and his wife [[Margaret Talbot, Countess of Shrewsbury|Lady Margaret Beauchamp]].{{sfn|Richmond|2004}} Her younger sister was [[Lady Eleanor Talbot]], believed to have been [[Edward IV of England|King Edward IV]]'s mistress.{{sfn|Pollard|2004}} Elizabeth's maternal grandparents were [[Richard de Beauchamp, 13th Earl of Warwick]] and Elizabeth de Berkeley. One of her brothers was [[John Talbot, 1st Viscount Lisle]], a nobleman and soldier.

==Marriage==
She was married to [[John de Mowbray, 4th Duke of Norfolk|John de Mowbray]]. He succeeded his father as [[Duke of Norfolk]] in 1461, making her the Duchess of Norfolk by marriage. They had only one surviving daughter, who inherited the Warwick estates.

* [[Anne de Mowbray, 8th Countess of Norfolk]] (10 December 1472 – 1481), married [[Richard of Shrewsbury, 1st Duke of York]], a son of [[Edward IV of England]] and one of the [[Princes in the Tower]]. Anne died at the age of 8.{{sfn|Weir|2008|p=141}}

