'''Essex Finch, Countess of Nottingham''' (c.1652 &ndash; 23 March 1684), formerly Lady Essex Rich, was the first wife of [[Daniel Finch, 2nd Earl of Nottingham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp51780/essex-finch-nee-rich-countess-of-nottingham|title=Essex Finch (née Rich), Countess of Nottingham (c.1652&ndash;1684)|website=National Gallery|access-date=26 February 2018}}</ref><ref>G.E. Cokayne; with Vicary Gibbs, H.A. Doubleday, Geoffrey H. White, Duncan Warrand and Lord Howard de Walden, editors, The Complete Peerage of England, Scotland, Ireland, Great Britain and the United Kingdom, Extant, Extinct or Dormant, new ed., 13 volumes in 14 (1910-1959; reprint in 6 volumes, Gloucester, U.K.: Alan Sutton Publishing, 2000), volume III, page 283.</ref>

Essex was the youngest daughter of [[Robert Rich, 3rd Earl of Warwick]], and his second wife Anne Cheeke. She was named after her mother's mother, who was also descended from [[Robert Rich, 1st Earl of Warwick]]. Following her mother's death, Essex and her sisters were brought up in the household of her father's brother, [[Charles Rich, 4th Earl of Warwick]].<ref name="huntington">{{cite web|url=http://emuseum.huntington.org/people/3346/lady-essex-rich-finch-later-countess-of-nottingham;jsessionid=85A6360E46289EA9E19E13AAFDAF6D12|title=Lady Essex (Rich) Finch, later Countess of Nottingham|website=Huntington e-Museum|access-date=26 February 2018}}</ref>

Husbands proposed for Lady Essex Rich included the son of [[Baron Berkeley of Stratton]] and Thomas Vane.<ref name="huntington"/> However, on 16 June 1674, she married Daniel Finch at [[Leez Priory]], near [[Felsted]], and they moved in with his parents at [[Kensington Palace]].<ref>[http://www.oxforddnb.com/public/lotw/7.html ODNB, "Daniel Finch"]</ref> The couple had eight children but only one daughter survived to adulthood:

*Mary Finch (1677-1718), who married [[William Savile, 2nd Marquess of Halifax]], as his second wife, following the death of his first wife Elizabeth Grimston. Halifax died in 1700 and she then married [[John Ker, 1st Duke of Roxburghe]].<ref>''Burke's Peerage'' (1939), s.v. Roxburghe.</ref>

The Countess of Nottingham died in childbirth, and was buried in the family vault at [[Ravenstone, Buckinghamshire|Ravenstone]].<ref name="huntington"/> Following her death, her husband remarried, his second wife being the [[Anne Finch, Countess of Nottingham|Hon. Anne Hatton]], by whom he had several children.

